*sigh* I wish I were wise.  Then I could comfortably, cleverly and completely explain that circumstance to my satisfaction, and I would be content and... go off and be wise somewhere else, or something.  But since I'm a lobotomized maroon, I will spew out something that isn't exactly what I meant.  I can already feel it happening...<br>
<br>
I'm in a one-EQ-player relationship.  My spouse is very displeased with it, and to be perfectly fair that displeasure is not entirely unwarranted.  Up until several months ago, I *did* spend too much time on it, relative to the number of waking hours in the day.  I spent more time in game than in relationship.<br>
<br>
But Everquest is just a symptom of a problem or issue, not the cause.  For me, before Everquest there was Team Fortress Classic in the /tmp clan.  Before that, individual PC games.  I love games, PC or otherwise.  I love to compete, on computer and off, though I don't give a saurek's hiney who wins -- I just love the feeling of play.  I love to interact with others, too, online, or performing in person, or through writing.<br>
<br>
My spouse... is not like that.  Keeping long and boring details to a minimum, her idea of fun and community, and mine, simply do not intersect.  The things I love to do, for her are either boring or annoying or intimidating.  Guess what?  The things *she* loves to do... to me, same story.  Who's right?  Nobody -- it's simply a case of being out of sync where fun comes in.<br>
<br>
It's not specifically about EQ, it's about the experiences and bonds that you share.  Everquest isn't a guaranteed addiction, but it's a powerful relationship-forming tool.  If you are the kind of person that has a deep affinity for that kind of thing, and your partner isn't... there's a VERY big conflict heading over the horizon.<br>
<br>
&quot;Give it up -- no game is worth losing your (partner).&quot;  I've seen this a lot, and I think it hits wide of the mark.  If you have a lot of other fun things you do with your spouse, and EQ suddenly arrived and tore you away from all of it, then maybe that's the right answer.  <br>
<br>
But if EQ is just another manifestation of things you deeply value to relax or have fun, then that's not reasonable at all.  It's no more fair than to say to the other person, &quot;You must stop watching TV (or reading, or gardening a lot or whatever) and start playing Everquest with your husband -- it's the only way to save the marriage.&quot;  Both are polarized requirements that are doomed to failure by their exclusivity.  <br>
